This video reminds me of the one time:

It was like 4 am and everyone was asleep. I was playing games, sitting on my bed under my blanket. I felt a pinch on my foot. It hurt but I didn’t really mind it, until I realised what it’s like to get bit by a bug. It took me like 10 minuets to realise this... because I’m stupid. I don’t know why I’d feel a sharp pinch under my blankets on my bed. Anyways, I immediately grabbed my phone, yeeted off my bed, and hopped on a chair in my room. The lights were off, which made it worse, so I put on the flashlight on my phone (still standing on the chair). I looked at my foot, and I had a big azz bump with 2 fang marks. I realised that I had a few friends visit me that weekend, and by friends I mean a family of brown roclus’s. I see brown roclus a lot (even tho they are big af) but this still sent shivers down my spine. I opened my messaging app, and texted my dad like

“DAD”
“DAD”
“A BIG AF SPIDER BIT ME!”
“HELP!”

My dad was asleep on the couch in the living room (since my dad doesn’t know YouTube exist, the tv is his life.) and I could hear the sound of the messages coming in. Than I texted my sister the same thing. She texted me.

“AHAHAHAHHAHAHAHA.”

Now I was like, this is survival, baby, because no one was gonna help me. (Why did I even text my sister?! She was in Paris.) I was thinking of ways to sleep without a spider biting me. My dad heard the messages, got up and opened my door. He said “What are you texting me for?!” In his Louisiana accent. “A spider bit me!” I said.

My dad literally “tch” me! Then he walked away. I wasn’t suprised bc I know my dad... I was really mad though.
But since the lights were on, I could see the floor. So I ran out the door, but than I was like “dude, where am I gonna sleep.”






To cut the story short, I slept on the counter in the bathroom. I won’t say it was a smart idea.... I will say it worked.

So, to anyone curious what this is. There is a parasite that can inflict various bugs, including spiders, praying mantises and others. The parasite eventually begins to take over, mainly a night. What it does is try to get the creature wet, once it does get wet the parasite kills the bug and sprouts out so it can grow. Now, this all from memory but I'll try to answer a few questions.

Is it worm?
No, fairly sure it's a type of plant or fungi.

Why did the bug spray not kill the "worm"?
If it isn't a worm, obvious why. If it is, well bug spray normally doesn't work on non-flying insects and it's pretty rare. The spider, nevertheless, died due the fact that it got wet. The parasite is most likely immune to the spray and survives.

Why does it just splurt out like that?
As I stated previously, it causes a reaction that causes the thing to grow. Becoming wet is normally a sign of rain, the perfect condition to grow. If you watch any video of this parasite, it's always very quick but it normally grows upwards.

This relates to the fact that nematomorpha often tie themselves in knots. They can be discovered in damp areas such as watering troughs, swimming pools, streams, puddles, and cisterns. The adult worms are free-living, but the larvae are parasitic on arthropods, such as beetles, cockroaches, mantids, orthopterans, and crustaceans. They can reach in extreme cases up to 2 metres.

I would keep the crickets in a small container until it was time to feed. One morning when I went to remove a cricket I found the cricket dead, and a long thin worm inside the container, probably 8 inches long and as thick as a pin. I knew I did not put any sort of worm in the container, and had never seen anything like it. I immediately started researching what the heck I had come across and found out that it was actually a Horsehair Worm, the same type of parasite as this Spider Worm, but one that made the cricket the host instead of a spider. Disgusting yet fascinating.
